WEBVTT

00:03.522 --> 00:07.307
Each year, Gospel and Life offers a daily devotional during the season of Lent.

00:07.687 --> 00:10.210
The 40 days from Ash Wednesday through Good Friday.

00:10.671 --> 00:15.336
You can sign up to receive these daily devotionals by email at gospelandlife.com.

00:15.557 --> 00:18.000
That's gospelandlife.com.

00:18.180 --> 00:20.943
Now here's Dr. Keller with today's teaching.

00:28.092 --> 00:33.298
We're spending a couple of weeks on the passage that you've got written out for you.

00:34.306 --> 00:39.372
in the bulletin, 1 Peter chapter 1 verses 13 to 21.

00:39.592 --> 00:45.058
And I'm going to read again, like I did last week, just the first part, 13 to 16.

00:45.098 --> 00:53.247
Therefore, prepare your minds for action.

00:54.468 --> 00:55.669
Be self-controlled.

00:56.510 --> 01:03.538
Set your hope fully on the grace to be given you when Jesus Christ is revealed as obedient children

01:03.906 --> 01:07.952
Do not conform to the evil desires you had when you lived in ignorance.

01:09.013 --> 01:19.688
But just as He who called you is holy, so be holy in all you do, for it is written, be holy because I am holy."

01:21.350 --> 01:22.632
Excuse me, this is God's Word.

01:24.474 --> 01:28.360
What we looked at last week was just a definition of holiness.

01:28.400 --> 01:28.840
That's all.

01:28.880 --> 01:30.162
We didn't have much time.

01:30.242 --> 01:40.616
Next week, this week and next week and the following week, we're going to look at how that plays out, because this is all about holiness and what it means to be holy.

01:41.257 --> 01:45.904
And we said that Peter, when he quotes this verse, be holy for I am holy.

01:46.605 --> 01:48.648
He's pulling something out of the book of Leviticus.

01:48.668 --> 01:54.636
There's a number of places where Leviticus says, where God says in Leviticus, be holy for I am holy.

01:55.197 --> 01:59.122
And the word used there, the Hebrew word used there, kadosh means

02:00.034 --> 02:02.516
to be separated, to be set apart.

02:04.258 --> 02:11.465
And therefore, this word holy, when it refers to God and refers to human beings, it's both the same and yet it's obviously different.

02:11.766 --> 02:15.549
When we talk about God being holy, we mean he's set apart.

02:15.589 --> 02:17.051
He's set above us.

02:17.672 --> 02:18.813
He's off the scale.

02:19.694 --> 02:21.315
He's transcendently above us.

02:21.355 --> 02:22.336
He's not like us.

02:22.957 --> 02:24.618
He's infinitely exalted above us.

02:25.439 --> 02:28.242
But when we talk about human beings being holy,

02:28.866 --> 02:32.229
The word set apart has a different aspect to it.

02:33.190 --> 02:35.473
We mean that we are set apart for God's use.

02:36.634 --> 02:39.937
To be holy means to be holy is.

02:41.519 --> 02:43.561
So let me give you an example.

02:43.621 --> 02:47.645
Here you are reading the newspaper and you read it and it's all for your information.

02:47.665 --> 02:53.270
You read 20 articles, 30 articles and you get through it and it's all helpful to you.

02:53.290 --> 02:57.074
But suddenly you come upon one particular article

02:57.602 --> 02:58.683
that you want to use.

02:59.665 --> 03:02.669
It's an article that really has something in it.

03:02.689 --> 03:06.994
You want to use it because you're writing something.

03:07.014 --> 03:08.116
You're writing some copy.

03:08.136 --> 03:09.778
You're writing a paper for a class.

03:10.459 --> 03:11.600
You're preparing a talk.

03:11.620 --> 03:13.322
You're doing a sales pitch or something.

03:13.823 --> 03:15.165
So you say, I need that.

03:15.825 --> 03:19.110
Now, when you need something, what do you do with it out of the newspaper?

03:20.231 --> 03:20.892
You cut it out.

03:21.453 --> 03:25.618
You separate it from the newspaper so that it's yours.

03:26.146 --> 03:32.213
He won't be of use to you if you don't separate it from the rest of the paper, so it's with you and it's for your use.

03:33.154 --> 03:35.978
When the Bible talks about holiness, it's saying the very same thing.

03:37.159 --> 03:38.941
What it means to be holy is to be cut out.

03:39.622 --> 03:40.944
It means to be separated.

03:41.004 --> 03:45.690
It means to be set apart for God's exclusive use.

03:45.790 --> 03:53.259
And that's why last week we said holiness is a lot, lot, lot more than just simply obeying a set of rules.

03:54.140 --> 03:55.922
It's to be in mind.

03:56.354 --> 04:00.441
and in will and in heart, and in every way, it means to be holy gods.

04:00.461 --> 04:02.845
It means to belong to God is exactly what it means.

04:02.865 --> 04:07.674
Just like, you know, here's your newspaper and you cut something out, so it's yours and you set it apart.

04:08.195 --> 04:09.297
That's what it means to be holy.

04:10.318 --> 04:12.482
It means to be completely at the disposal of God.

04:12.502 --> 04:14.746
It means to put yourself completely in his hands.

04:14.786 --> 04:17.130
It means to want that, to want to be used.

04:20.617 --> 04:21.458
You know, what's

04:21.666 --> 04:25.291
I mentioned this at the end of the four o'clock service, but I didn't mention it this morning.

04:25.311 --> 04:32.803
There was a, the last hymn that we sang in the morning service, we rest on thee, our shield and our defender.

04:34.165 --> 04:48.186
Interesting historical note is that the six missionaries in the early 1950s who went, sought to go to Ecuador and they sought to contact a very primitive tribe.

04:48.646 --> 04:51.090
They wanted to meet the tribe, they wanted to learn their language,

04:51.426 --> 04:53.169
They wanted to give them the written language.

04:53.209 --> 05:01.082
This was an illiterate tribe and they wanted to put the language down on paper so that they could teach them to read and write and to translate the Bible into their language.

05:02.364 --> 05:08.674
In the night before these six missionaries went to contact the Indians, they sang this hymn all together.

05:09.956 --> 05:11.779
We rest on thee, our shield and our defender.

05:12.480 --> 05:14.664
We go not forth alone against the foe.

05:15.425 --> 05:18.450
Strong and nice strength, safe in thy keeping tender.

05:19.042 --> 05:21.506
We rest on thee, and in thy name we go.

05:22.728 --> 05:24.871
Strong and I strengthen, safe and like keeping tender.

05:25.492 --> 05:28.897
And the next day they were all spirited death by the Indians.

05:29.979 --> 05:31.622
So I guess the hymn didn't work.

05:32.543 --> 05:33.885
I guess the Christian faith didn't work.

05:33.905 --> 05:40.195
We know the wife of one of those missionaries, Elizabeth Eliot, she's been here to speak.

05:40.255 --> 05:45.123
And she often refers to the fact that this particular hymn was sung by them the night before.

05:45.824 --> 05:47.186
We rest on thee.

05:47.970 --> 05:51.036
We want to put ourselves in your hands.

05:51.617 --> 05:52.960
So they were all spirited at.

05:53.000 --> 05:55.284
Does that mean that it didn't work?

05:55.384 --> 05:58.410
No, because you see, what does it mean to be holy?

05:58.450 --> 06:01.416
It means to say to God, use me.

06:02.939 --> 06:05.043
When I know I'm going, I know I'm at work.

06:05.063 --> 06:07.808
We're on a collision course with modern culture.

06:07.909 --> 06:08.450
I know that.

06:09.311 --> 06:10.674
We're on a collision course.

06:10.978 --> 06:14.262
We can handle the idea of knowing God sometimes, can't we?

06:14.362 --> 06:16.024
Oh yeah, we wanna know God, that's great.

06:16.324 --> 06:17.966
We wanna experience His love, that's great.

06:18.466 --> 06:19.708
Even the idea of obeying God.

06:19.788 --> 06:21.089
Well, you can sort of get into that.

06:21.149 --> 06:23.572
There's design, there's rules.

06:23.672 --> 06:26.255
Okay, I can do that, but this is beyond the rules.

06:27.216 --> 06:32.422
What it means to be holy means to be cut out, to be with God so that God can use you.

06:33.163 --> 06:39.730
To be holy means to say, use me Lord, use even me in any way

06:40.930 --> 06:42.132
And of course, they were used.

06:42.953 --> 06:44.074
They were mightily used.

06:44.094 --> 06:44.975
They were martyrs.

06:45.936 --> 06:47.819
Not exactly the way you had in mind, right?

06:47.859 --> 06:48.620
When you sing that hymn.

06:49.180 --> 06:51.163
But you know, we rest on thee.

06:52.945 --> 06:58.332
Jesus, our righteousness, our sure foundation, our prince of glory, our king of love.

06:59.534 --> 07:05.141
Yes, in thy name, O captain of salvation, in thy dear name, all other names above.

07:06.302 --> 07:07.323
That's what it means to be holy.

07:07.363 --> 07:09.426
It means to finally say,

07:09.794 --> 07:10.896
I'm not mine anymore.

07:10.916 --> 07:12.559
I'm bought with a price."

07:13.741 --> 07:14.061
All right.

07:14.282 --> 07:19.391
Now, having said that, somebody says, who needs this?

07:20.693 --> 07:25.481
You need this because, believe it or not, we're built for this.

07:27.004 --> 07:31.692
Now, once you get that down, you begin to realize that holiness is not easy at all.

07:31.852 --> 07:33.255
It's not like obeying the rules.

07:33.315 --> 07:35.218
It's not like obeying the regulations.

07:35.490 --> 07:41.177
holiness is getting yourself mind, will, and emotions to belong to God.

07:41.658 --> 07:48.707
That's the reason why the English word holy, the English word holy doesn't mean separate, separated, cut out, the way the Hebrew word means.

07:49.688 --> 07:57.618
I think the English word holy, of course, is though also helpful because it comes from the word to be whole, to be completely God's.

07:57.986 --> 08:00.729
So to be holy means to make yourself holy gods.

08:00.749 --> 08:01.349
What does that mean?

08:01.730 --> 08:08.637
It means to take every part of you, the whole person, and that's why tonight, next week, and the next week, I wanna talk about the different aspects of our lives.

08:08.657 --> 08:18.466
What it means to be holy is not just obey the rules, but to give him your mind holy, to give him your will holy, and to give him your heart holy.

08:18.807 --> 08:26.194
Now tonight, let's just take a look and we'll see that as soon as Peter says, I want you to be holy, he starts the section out by saying,

08:27.970 --> 08:29.592
Gird up the loins of your mind.

08:29.652 --> 08:32.735
Now, I know that's not what it says in your translation.

08:33.276 --> 08:37.541
It says, therefore, prepare your minds for action and be self-controlled.

08:38.041 --> 08:40.784
But these first two phrases is what we're going to look at tonight.

08:41.445 --> 08:51.576
Because these first two phrases tell us that you can't be holy unless you prepare your minds for action, unless you let your minds belong to God.

08:52.617 --> 08:53.578
What does this term mean?

08:53.939 --> 08:57.042
Now, I mentioned this last week, but now we'll get into it a little bit more.

08:57.154 --> 09:07.967
The actual Greek, if it was translated literally, it would be almost incomprehensible to modern people, because literally it says, gird up the loins of your mind.

09:08.687 --> 09:24.786
Now what that means, as I think I alluded to last week, is in those days, people in the Greek or Roman world, people, men and women were long robes, and if you wanted to do something that was strenuous, if you had a run or if you had to do some evasive action or something very hard,

09:24.866 --> 09:31.055
you would gird up the loins, which means your gird, the girdle, the girdle was, this belt.

09:31.616 --> 09:40.589
There was a belt around your waist, and what you would do is you'd pick up your flowing robes and you'd stick them in the girder around your loins.

09:41.430 --> 09:46.918
So that basically your legs were free, and in many cases your arms were free, and so you're ready for action.

09:47.739 --> 09:52.786
The closest thing we'd have in a modern idiom would be roll up your sleeves, you know, get ready.

09:53.250 --> 09:55.313
But it doesn't just say gird up the loins.

09:55.373 --> 09:57.595
It says gird up the loins of your mind.

09:59.538 --> 10:02.942
And the word that's used here is dia noia.

10:03.462 --> 10:05.325
Dia is a Greek word for through.

10:05.365 --> 10:09.330
It's the word diameter, the meter that goes through, the center of the circle.

10:10.111 --> 10:11.132
Dia means through.

10:11.172 --> 10:14.916
And noia has to do with noose, means has to do with the mind.

10:15.437 --> 10:19.382
And so it literally means to think through rationally.

10:20.543 --> 10:22.706
There's a couple places in the Bible where it means

10:22.850 --> 10:23.711
to debate.

10:24.392 --> 10:30.121
So, for example, the same word shows up in Hebrews 12 where it says, let the Word of God de anoia you, let it debate with you.

10:30.182 --> 10:31.564
It's a very, very interesting word.

10:31.624 --> 10:43.442
It literally means to think things something through, to summons up all of your rational powers, all of your capacities for thought and reflection and consideration, all of the logic that you can muster.

10:44.604 --> 10:48.370
It's a word that's used, it would include both induction and deduction.

10:49.314 --> 10:57.923
You see, if you ever watch these great murder mysteries that BBC puts out, Sherlock Holmes and Agatha Christie mysteries, you have all the facts.

10:58.984 --> 11:01.827
But you can never, if it's a good plot, you can't figure it out.

11:01.907 --> 11:02.147
Why?

11:02.187 --> 11:12.317
Because the good murder mystery writers give you solutions to the murder mystery which are rational but counterintuitive.

11:13.578 --> 11:15.520
In other words, a really good murder mystery.

11:15.881 --> 11:17.202
You have all the clues yourself.

11:18.114 --> 11:24.782
In a good murder mystery, you're baffled till the end, even though you have all the clues yourself, but you just weren't able to think through the clues.

11:25.423 --> 11:26.625
You were following your hunches.

11:27.185 --> 11:28.467
You were following your prejudices.

11:28.507 --> 11:33.533
You were following your intuition, but the great sleuth, whoever, thinks through.

11:33.554 --> 11:37.919
And when it's all done, you read the end of the book and you say, why didn't I see that?

11:38.079 --> 11:39.381
Of course I could have seen that.

11:39.401 --> 11:40.242
I didn't think through.

11:40.723 --> 11:42.905
I didn't summons up all of my rational faculties.

11:43.326 --> 11:46.610
That's the word that Peter uses.

11:47.458 --> 11:54.268
And what it means is that you can't be a Christian, you can't be holy unless you use your mind.

11:56.731 --> 11:58.915
It's critical that you be able to think.

12:00.176 --> 12:12.434
You know, there's a place in Romans, Romans chapter 10, verse 2, and where Paul says about some Christians, he says, I bear witness to them that they have zeal, but without knowledge.

12:13.346 --> 12:14.287
Isn't that interesting?

12:14.367 --> 12:15.729
They have zeal, but without knowledge.

12:15.749 --> 12:18.472
What he's saying is they have a lot of enthusiasm for the Lord.

12:18.552 --> 12:20.213
A lot of enthusiasm, they don't think.

12:21.855 --> 12:23.297
And that's a criticism.

12:24.318 --> 12:27.241
You see, heat without light, no good.

12:28.623 --> 12:32.066
Enthusiasm, but not rational, not thinking.

12:33.688 --> 12:40.736
There's one, John Mackay once said, commitment without reflection is fanaticism.

12:41.417 --> 12:42.738
Reflection without commitment.

12:42.946 --> 12:43.767
is paralysis.

12:44.849 --> 12:47.033
You can deal with that knowledge, knowledge without zeal, no good.

12:47.734 --> 12:48.676
You've got to use the mind.

12:48.716 --> 12:53.084
Now I know this doesn't seem like something that many people believe.

12:53.284 --> 13:05.405
In fact, I go so far as to say that the average person in Manhattan is shocked if they hear you a believing Christian, reflective and thoughtful, they're amazed.

13:06.066 --> 13:08.210
The average person in Manhattan believes

13:08.834 --> 13:15.682
that if you're educated, if you're thoughtful, if you're rational, and so on, you wouldn't believe.

13:16.502 --> 13:22.029
Most people in Manhattan think that Christianity is for people who don't want to use their mind.

13:22.529 --> 13:23.390
It's not for thinkers.

13:24.171 --> 13:27.575
In fact, if you're going to be a Christian, you've got a jettison, your thought.

13:27.935 --> 13:29.717
You have to jettison your rationality.

13:29.737 --> 13:32.400
You have to jettison your capacities for thought and reflection.

13:32.420 --> 13:33.161
You have to get rid of them.

13:33.481 --> 13:37.746
And you sort of surrender yourself into the realm of feeling, and you take this leap of faith.

13:39.842 --> 13:59.486
If you say to somebody here, and you sound like you've reasoned it out and you sound thoughtful and rational about it, and you say, I believe that Jesus Christ is the Son of God, preexisting, Son of God, who was, who came to earth and was born of a virgin and lived a perfect life and died to pay the debt for us.

13:59.566 --> 14:01.348
And now he was physically raised from the dead.

14:01.788 --> 14:03.551
And now he sits at the right hand of the Father.

14:03.851 --> 14:08.276
And when we believe in him, he pardons our sins and he puts the Holy Spirit in us so that we experience the new birth.

14:08.316 --> 14:09.778
And someday he's going to come back

14:10.754 --> 14:19.683
And we will all see him, and he will bring about judgment of all human beings, and he will inaugurate the New Heavens and the New Earth, and they look at you and they can't believe it.

14:20.864 --> 14:25.689
Because the typical person in New York says, look, I know there's still people that believe that.

14:26.430 --> 14:34.138
Members of the proletariat, the oppressed working classes and the poor people, they've been kept away from knowledge and enlightenment, you see, and it's not their fault.

14:34.178 --> 14:35.959
If they want to yell hallelujah, that's fine.

14:36.260 --> 14:38.482
But you've gone to college, you should know better.

14:39.746 --> 14:46.055
And this attitude, this utterly paternalistic attitude is a complete misconception of Christianity.

14:46.675 --> 14:56.529
I want to show you what Peter says here and what it says all the way through the Bible is not only may Christians think and use their mind, but Christians must think.

14:57.110 --> 15:04.139
Christianity, let me just tell you two things this evening, and this is the first one which I've already gotten into.

15:04.179 --> 15:08.946
The first thing is Christianity requires you to use your mind

15:09.858 --> 15:11.380
It requires you to think.

15:12.282 --> 15:17.610
It requires you to summons up all of your rational capacities.

15:18.071 --> 15:21.857
It requires and demands and encourages it and stimulates it.

15:23.179 --> 15:24.581
Not just here, not just here.

15:24.601 --> 15:29.008
For example, thinking is fundamental to becoming a Christian.

15:29.128 --> 15:38.162
If you look further on in the chapter, chapter 1, verse 22, it says, you have purified yourselves by obeying the truth.

15:39.522 --> 15:45.007
Verse 23, it says, you're born again, not by imperishable seed, but by the living and during word of God.

15:46.329 --> 15:47.570
There's another passage like it.

15:47.630 --> 15:49.031
It's in Romans 6, 17.

15:49.091 --> 15:56.339
It says, but though you were servants of sin, you obeyed from the heart the form of teaching which was delivered to you.

15:58.040 --> 16:00.022
Now, all of those texts say this.

16:01.363 --> 16:08.050
Being a Christian, becoming a Christian, being born again is more than just thinking, but not less.

16:08.706 --> 16:10.749
You have to grasp the form of teaching.

16:10.769 --> 16:12.772
You have to understand the gospel.

16:13.273 --> 16:16.417
It has to be something that you grasp and you see you have to think with.

16:16.437 --> 16:18.380
You're born again, through what?

16:18.700 --> 16:21.604
Through receiving the word, a form of teaching, a system of doctrine.

16:22.906 --> 16:25.991
Oh, of course, it says, obeyed from the heart, the form of teaching.

16:26.311 --> 16:27.453
That's how you became a Christian.

16:27.693 --> 16:29.135
Well, there's the whole person.

16:29.556 --> 16:31.959
You obey, that's the will from the heart, you see?

16:32.460 --> 16:33.361
The form of teaching.

16:34.002 --> 16:36.786
But, but how wrong it is

16:37.058 --> 16:40.541
for people to think that Christianity is basically emotional or volitional.

16:40.581 --> 16:40.942
Oh no.

16:42.884 --> 16:44.025
It's rational as well.

16:44.505 --> 16:46.187
It's fundamentally rational.

16:46.207 --> 16:50.411
Say, there are all kinds of churches, friends, fundamentalist churches.

16:51.752 --> 16:52.393
What does that mean?

16:53.754 --> 16:58.499
Churches that are legalistic, that are authoritarian, they put all the stress on the will.

17:00.080 --> 17:01.742
They say, just don't think.

17:01.902 --> 17:03.824
Just do whatever I tell you to do.

17:04.124 --> 17:04.564
Don't think.

17:04.885 --> 17:05.585
Hear the rules.

17:05.706 --> 17:06.226
Do them.

17:06.914 --> 17:07.435
Don't think.

17:07.775 --> 17:09.197
Just obey whatever I tell you.

17:09.378 --> 17:09.858
Don't think.

17:09.918 --> 17:11.000
Don't read the Bible for yourself.

17:11.060 --> 17:11.681
Don't work it out.

17:11.721 --> 17:12.322
Don't think it out.

17:12.582 --> 17:13.424
Just do what I say.

17:13.484 --> 17:14.806
There's a lot of churches like that.

17:15.006 --> 17:18.611
But on the other hand, the liberal churches are just as anti-intellectual.

17:19.132 --> 17:29.527
There's a Unitarian church down in Murray Hill I went by and there was an interesting plaque up and it said, we are a group of people who all work hard to love people and be compassionate and to work for a better city.

17:29.848 --> 17:31.410
And it doesn't matter what you believe.

17:32.450 --> 17:33.531
We don't care what you believe.

17:33.551 --> 17:35.894
We don't care what you think, as long as you do good deeds.

17:35.994 --> 17:37.115
That's what it says on the plaque.

17:38.116 --> 17:41.359
Now, besides the fact that that's absolutely contradictory.

17:42.100 --> 17:47.426
I mean, why would you do good deeds unless you believe that human beings were dignity and were worth doing good deeds for?

17:47.466 --> 17:48.167
I mean, that's silly.

17:48.187 --> 17:49.528
And science isn't going to tell you that.

17:49.588 --> 17:51.390
Science is going to tell you it's your bag of chemicals.

17:51.991 --> 17:53.452
I mean, that's a religious belief.

17:53.492 --> 17:56.495
And so it sounds really nice to say, we don't care what you believe.

17:56.515 --> 17:57.236
That's ridiculous.

17:57.256 --> 17:58.898
They do care what you believe.

18:00.450 --> 18:01.532
But you see what they're saying?

18:01.813 --> 18:02.875
It doesn't matter what you believe.

18:02.895 --> 18:04.639
It doesn't matter what you think, just what you do.

18:04.860 --> 18:07.345
That's as anti-intellectual as the fundamentalist.

18:09.150 --> 18:10.011
Doctrine doesn't matter.

18:10.292 --> 18:11.294
Studying the Bible doesn't matter.

18:11.395 --> 18:12.838
Figuring out what it teaches doesn't matter.

18:14.081 --> 18:18.290
On the other hand, you have a lot of high churches, churches that put all the emphasis on ritual.

18:19.362 --> 18:22.165
And they, too, they say, well, you believe this, you believe that.

18:22.205 --> 18:23.667
Doesn't matter, the point is the ritual.

18:23.707 --> 18:26.050
And so you get caught up in this aesthetic experience.

18:26.070 --> 18:34.680
And all the people love it because of the music and because of the architecture and because of the, in some ways, the glamour of it, the aestheticness of it.

18:35.661 --> 18:37.363
It's all the emphasis is on the emotion.

18:39.245 --> 18:42.809
The sermon is five to seven minutes long and everybody sleeps through it.

18:44.371 --> 18:46.674
We don't care about thinking, it's the feeling.

18:47.010 --> 18:54.299
And then there's a lot of other evangelical churches that are put all the emphasis on the feeling, all the emphasis on the catharsis, all the emphasis on the emotion that you feel it.

18:55.380 --> 19:06.694
My dear friends, the Bible says to become a Christian engages the emotions and engages the will, but it also engages the mind just as fundamentally.

19:08.316 --> 19:09.979
You can't be a Christian unless you think.

19:10.019 --> 19:12.001
You can't grow as a Christian unless you think.

19:12.321 --> 19:15.986
You can't grow in holiness unless you gird up the loins of your mind.

19:17.122 --> 19:17.643
fundamental.

19:19.385 --> 19:20.907
Let me give you another example of how.

19:21.228 --> 19:25.774
So the first thing is, I said Christianity demands that you think even to become a Christian.

19:26.395 --> 19:31.362
Secondly, faith is really an exercise in thinking as well.

19:31.582 --> 19:35.567
A lot of people say, well, you have faith, but I'm a rational person.

19:36.949 --> 19:37.550
Let me tell you.

19:38.251 --> 19:38.511
C.S.

19:38.531 --> 19:41.836
Lewis gives you a great example of how faith really operates.

19:42.297 --> 19:42.517
C.S.

19:42.557 --> 19:44.800
Lewis says, let's just say you have to go to a doctor.

19:45.241 --> 19:46.322
So you study

19:47.426 --> 19:50.051
everything you can to find out about that doctor.

19:50.112 --> 19:52.677
You talk to people who have been to the doctor.

19:54.320 --> 19:59.050
So you say, hey, here's a doctor and she is a good doctor, but I want to find out about her.

19:59.070 --> 20:02.097
So what you do is you go and you talk to a number of people and they're all say, oh, she's great.

20:02.137 --> 20:06.546
I've been to her and I ached and I pained and everything and now I'm all better.

20:06.626 --> 20:10.172
And then you talk to other doctors and you find out she is the leader in the field.

20:10.512 --> 20:17.203
And then you study the charts or you study the history and you were able, you probably have to break into illegally into files to find this out.

20:17.223 --> 20:18.405
And she's never lost a patient.

20:19.787 --> 20:20.468
So what have you done?

20:20.869 --> 20:21.610
You've thought it through.

20:21.630 --> 20:26.117
You rationally have come to see that the evidence is that she's a very good doctor.

20:27.039 --> 20:34.130
But on the day that you have to get there, on the day you have to go, on the day you have to report to the hospital, on the day she has to cut you open,

20:35.010 --> 20:38.716
It's the last minute you panic and you run and you decide I'm not going to go through it.

20:38.736 --> 20:39.216
What happened?

20:40.398 --> 20:41.139
You lost faith.

20:41.560 --> 20:44.324
Well, does this mean you lost faith because you started to reason?

20:44.544 --> 20:45.386
You started to think?

20:46.808 --> 20:46.888
Huh?

20:46.908 --> 20:48.550
Is faith the opposite of reason and thinking?

20:48.671 --> 20:49.432
Absolutely not.

20:50.473 --> 20:57.804
You lost faith because you stopped thinking, because you stopped reasoning, because you stopped looking at the evidence and you listened to your emotions and you listened to your fears.

20:58.726 --> 21:01.650
It's silly to think that faith is the opposite of reason.

21:03.458 --> 21:06.403
Why is there so much pain and suffering in the world?

21:06.864 --> 21:12.774
And how do we handle it in a way that won't destroy us, but could actually make us stronger, wiser, and more hopeful?

21:13.516 --> 21:22.952
All month long on Gospel and Life, Tim Keller is teaching from the book of 1 Peter, and looking at how Peter encouraged early believers who were facing intense suffering and pain.

21:23.673 --> 21:26.258
In his book Walking with God Through Pain and Suffering,

21:26.306 --> 21:34.193
Dr. Keller takes a deeper look at how, with God's help, we can face life's most intense challenges and confront the hard questions on suffering.

21:34.733 --> 21:40.959
Through deep pastoral insight and real life stories, Dr. Keller explores how we can face pain and suffering in our own lives.

21:41.499 --> 21:51.007
This month, walking with God through pain and suffering is our thank you for your gift to help Gospel and Life share the message of Christ's love and compassion with people all over the world.

21:51.528 --> 21:56.292
So request your copy today at gospelandlife.com.

21:56.272 --> 22:04.119
Now here's Dr. Keller with the remainder of today's teaching.

22:04.139 --> 22:06.681
You know, here's a good quote.

22:06.701 --> 22:18.872
You know, the passage, the famous passage we used it in the confession of sin this morning, Matthew 6, where Jesus says, if you're worried, have no anxiety but think about the lilies of the field.

22:19.472 --> 22:20.513
God takes care of them.

22:20.553 --> 22:25.938
Think, have no anxiety but think about the birds of the air.

22:26.018 --> 22:29.323
takes care of them, oh ye of little faith," he says.

22:30.325 --> 22:34.211
If God takes care of the birds and the grass and you're more valuable than they, won't he take care of you?

22:34.312 --> 22:35.153
What is Jesus doing?

22:35.373 --> 22:38.118
He says, oh ye of little faith, you're not thinking.

22:38.158 --> 22:43.146
He doesn't say, if you want to have faith, stop thinking and just believe that's not faith.

22:43.166 --> 22:44.508
That's not what the Bible calls faith.

22:44.749 --> 22:50.358
Look, David Martin Lloyd-Jones in his great sermon on this passage, here's a quote from him.

22:51.019 --> 22:53.042
He says, Jesus Christ,

22:53.250 --> 22:57.435
insists that the whole trouble with people of little faith is they do not think.

22:59.016 --> 23:01.479
They don't gird up the loins of their minds, see?

23:01.499 --> 23:03.621
They allow circumstances to bludgeon them.

23:04.722 --> 23:05.403
Think about this.

23:05.483 --> 23:07.786
They allow their feelings to collar them.

23:09.027 --> 23:10.469
Now, the Bible is full of reasoning.

23:10.509 --> 23:12.691
We must never think of faith as something purely mystical.

23:12.751 --> 23:15.054
Faith progresses through thinking, Jesus tells us.

23:15.714 --> 23:16.896
Jesus says, look at the birds.

23:17.396 --> 23:18.077
Think about them.

23:18.317 --> 23:19.278
Draw your deductions.

23:19.458 --> 23:20.259
Look at the flowers.

23:20.540 --> 23:21.100
Do the same.

23:21.401 --> 23:22.802
That is the essence of worry.

23:23.042 --> 23:27.668
Instead of letting reason control your thoughts, other things have controlled them, and you go round and round in circles.

23:28.510 --> 23:29.391
That is not thinking.

23:30.332 --> 23:31.894
Worry is the absence of thinking.

23:32.095 --> 23:33.957
Unbelief is the absence of thinking.

23:34.017 --> 23:38.664
And for a Christian, a lack of faith is a failure to think.

23:39.965 --> 23:41.147
Throw it up the loins of your mind.

23:42.128 --> 23:51.922
Not only that, the Bible tells you that you can't grow in holiness unless you're willing to let God take over your thinking.

23:52.258 --> 24:00.209
It says in Ephesians 4, 22 to 24, be renewed through the renewal of your mind.

24:00.249 --> 24:06.677
That's the place where it says, put off the old self, put on the new and be renewed in the renewal of your mind.

24:06.737 --> 24:09.161
Now, please listen carefully to this.

24:09.721 --> 24:11.263
You can't bifurcate this.

24:12.465 --> 24:14.007
Jesus Christ demands all of you.

24:14.047 --> 24:19.314
And what this means is many of us come to Christianity

24:19.842 --> 24:22.685
wanting something emotional, wanting something personal.

24:23.246 --> 24:25.428
And we've already got ideas made up about things.

24:26.029 --> 24:30.314
We have cultural ideas, ideological ideas, ideas about how things ought to be.

24:30.994 --> 24:34.939
And we're desperately afraid that if we come to Christianity, it might change our minds.

24:35.880 --> 24:37.582
And we wouldn't want any of that thing to happen.

24:37.622 --> 24:41.186
We want the happiness, we want the joy, but we don't want anybody to change our minds.

24:41.666 --> 24:43.368
What kind of religion are you thinking about?

24:43.748 --> 24:44.690
Not Christianity.

24:45.350 --> 24:48.754
Christianity is not a religion strictly of the feelings.

24:49.698 --> 24:51.220
You have to grid up the lines of your mind.

24:51.240 --> 24:52.802
You have to submit intellectually.

24:52.862 --> 24:58.170
Jesus Christ has authority of you intellectually, not just personally, not just spiritually in some kind of way.

24:59.612 --> 25:00.333
Look at it this way.

25:00.353 --> 25:01.194
I'll put it this way.

25:01.575 --> 25:18.418
To renew your mind, to have a holy mind means that you must read ideology and culture and opinion through a biblical grid rather than read the Bible through a cultural and ideological grid.

25:19.810 --> 25:23.916
So let me just give you a couple of examples and just throw them out.

25:23.936 --> 25:36.355
One of the things that I found interesting about working when I did as a teacher at Westminster Seminary was that it was a very multi-ethnic body, and about 15 to 20% of the students were Korean.

25:37.417 --> 25:45.650
Now one of the things we found, especially with a couple of my Korean students and Korean friends, was, and most of the Korean students that I had were from Korea.

25:45.690 --> 25:48.594
They had flown from Seoul to America,

25:48.674 --> 25:51.217
And so they were immersed in their own Korean culture.

25:51.618 --> 25:55.242
We found out that when a Korean reads the words, obey your parents.

25:56.764 --> 26:03.872
And when an American reads the words in the Bible, obey your parents, we can come away with two completely different understandings.

26:04.013 --> 26:04.253
Why?

26:04.814 --> 26:09.860
Because though I'm a Christian, I'm an American and I am steeped in Western individualism.

26:10.360 --> 26:12.403
I am steeped in secular individualism.

26:13.224 --> 26:15.727
And so I read, obey your parents, and I think I know what it means.

26:16.448 --> 26:18.290
But I'm immediately reading it through my grid.

26:19.458 --> 26:32.955
And here's a Korean, and even though my Korean friend might be a Christian, just like I'm a Christian, I'm steeped in Western individualism, he or she might, though a Christian might be steeped in the collectivist Confucian culture of Korea.

26:34.897 --> 26:45.490
And one of the things that we slowly came to understand, when you, this is one of the great advantages of doing multicultural Bible studies, you know, you study the thing and you get totally different things out of the text and you say, what?

26:46.818 --> 26:48.200
and you begin to realize what you're doing.

26:48.541 --> 26:54.911
After a while, you begin to realize that if you really read what the Bible says, the Bible is not really a very Eastern or a very Western book.

26:56.854 --> 27:05.207
And the biblical understanding of parental authority really is not as authoritarian as the Korean nor is it as wimpy as the American.

27:05.808 --> 27:11.718
You have the American wimpy parental model where you sort of sit with the children and say, oh, you hit me.

27:11.838 --> 27:12.599
Did that feel good?

27:12.619 --> 27:14.322
How did that make you feel?

27:14.626 --> 27:16.629
Should we talk about it?

27:16.989 --> 27:18.431
That's right.

27:19.612 --> 27:21.295
And then you have the Korean parental medal.

27:21.315 --> 27:25.460
Oh, you hit me off with his head, upstairs.

27:25.500 --> 27:42.642
Now listen, come to realize after a while how hard it is to immerse yourself so much in the scripture that you start to let the scripture become a grid in your mind by which you can read your own culture.

27:42.754 --> 27:52.585
It takes a long time, but it mainly takes it to start with an act of the will and a willingness to submit your reason and submit your thinking to the Word of God and immerse your mind in it.

27:54.127 --> 28:10.386
One person says, a renewed mind is a trained, informed, equipped mind, equipped to sift the data through a framework of reference in your mind made up of biblical truths about the value and the nature of God, of human nature, of good and evil, of truth, authority and so on.

28:12.418 --> 28:13.519
Do you know what it's like to do that?

28:14.060 --> 28:17.885
Real quickly, I hate to criticize this article.

28:18.005 --> 28:23.011
I read an editorial last Sunday, I think it was, in The New York Times, and it was really a good article.

28:23.051 --> 28:26.736
So I hate to pick one bone with it, but it's an awfully good example of what I'm trying to say now.

28:27.577 --> 28:33.785
Anna Quinlan wrote an op-ed piece, and in it she quotes from Stephen Carter's new book, The Culture of Disbelief.

28:35.226 --> 28:41.394
And in that book, what she was saying is that there's a yawning spiritual vacuum

28:41.474 --> 28:42.776
in the lives of American people.

28:43.837 --> 28:53.430
And she says, we liberals have been fighting for individual rights for years, and now we're realizing, she says, that people need to feel that they're connected to something bigger than themselves.

28:54.311 --> 28:57.215
And this is what she, there's two quotes from the article.

28:57.336 --> 29:05.426
One is she says, we err when we presume that religious motives and religious sentiments are likely to be unliberal.

29:06.067 --> 29:10.994
And then she says, we liberals must acknowledge this, that while the rights of the individual are precious,

29:11.330 --> 29:12.471
at some deep level.

29:12.992 --> 29:14.834
Individualism alone does not suffice.

29:17.477 --> 29:22.902
The discussion must continue of what morality means of how to fill the spiritual vacuum.

29:23.183 --> 29:25.305
Now, here's the only thing I'm going to pick.

29:25.365 --> 29:25.986
I'm really happy.

29:26.026 --> 29:26.666
It was a great article.

29:26.706 --> 29:27.547
I was really glad she wrote it.

29:27.768 --> 29:28.628
But you see what she's saying?

29:29.449 --> 29:34.615
She's trying to say to all of her liberal friends, she says, you know, maybe it's good for us to get more religious.

29:34.835 --> 29:37.618
Not that it'll change your mind on any of your positions.

29:38.626 --> 29:41.930
You see, don't think that just because you become a Christian, you won't be a liberal.

29:41.970 --> 29:52.144
Now, I'm not here to tell you what becoming a Christian makes you on the political spectrum, because frankly, it's very hard, I think, to put Christians on the spectrums, but I'll tell you this.

29:53.145 --> 29:54.507
What kind of religion does she want?

29:56.109 --> 29:57.852
A religion totally a feeling?

29:58.352 --> 29:59.714
A religion totally a sentiment?

30:00.195 --> 30:04.401
She says, you know, you can get spiritual and it not really change your mind on the things you've already made up your mind about.

30:05.923 --> 30:07.024
There's a lot of religions like that.

30:07.104 --> 30:08.466
Just don't come to Christianity.

30:09.538 --> 30:11.680
Christianity says, you've got to be holy.

30:12.701 --> 30:13.823
You have to be holy His.

30:14.543 --> 30:16.546
You have to be willing to submit your mind.

30:17.166 --> 30:20.490
You have to be willing to say, boy, that's going to be uncomfortable for me to change my view on that.

30:20.510 --> 30:22.312
But is that what God actually teaches?

30:22.372 --> 30:32.403
And if you think that God is going to deal with you emotionally and spiritually and volitionally, if you withhold yourself from Him intellectually, does it make any sense?

30:33.004 --> 30:34.565
You've got to all come in or not come in.

30:35.366 --> 30:38.770
I had an old teacher used to say, if you come to the door,

30:39.650 --> 30:43.515
and knock on it, and I say, Tim, come on in, but Keller, stay out.

30:43.575 --> 30:44.095
What are you gonna do?

30:45.977 --> 30:46.919
It's pretty confusing.

30:48.761 --> 30:54.628
And if you say, Lord Jesus, I want you to come in and have this part of me, what you're really saying is come in, save your stay out, Lord.

30:55.509 --> 30:56.450
Oh, he never does that.

30:58.933 --> 31:01.075
One more thing.

31:02.036 --> 31:03.678
And last thing, but it's important.

31:05.040 --> 31:06.962
Not only would I like to show you,

31:07.522 --> 31:08.303
This is the last point.

31:08.323 --> 31:13.511
The last point is not only does the Bible insist that to be a Christian, you've got to think.

31:14.513 --> 31:22.466
To be a Christian, Christianity requires thinking, requires rationality, requires that, but not only that.

31:22.506 --> 31:26.392
This will stimulate you, I hope.

31:27.033 --> 31:32.882
I'd like to go so far so that it's the only thing in the world today that really does encourage thinking.

31:33.506 --> 31:34.307
and reason.

31:34.508 --> 31:37.252
It's the only thing that encourages, is the only thing that gives a basis for it.

31:37.272 --> 31:38.915
Let me do this quick.

31:39.435 --> 31:41.719
This is worth the end here.

31:41.759 --> 31:45.565
There's only three basic worldviews you can have right now today.

31:46.066 --> 31:50.272
There's been other worldviews, but there's only three basic philosophies of life that are out there.

31:50.953 --> 32:01.490
You've got scientific materialism, which says that there is no soul, there is no supernatural, there is no God, there is no heaven and hell, and therefore everything is an accident.

32:02.050 --> 32:04.433
And everything has a natural cause.

32:04.493 --> 32:08.978
Now, these people will tell you, ultimately, that means that your mind's an accident.

32:10.180 --> 32:17.529
And the thoughts you're having right now are just the chance reaction of molecules under your skull.

32:18.249 --> 32:19.671
They're just bouncing off of each other.

32:19.972 --> 32:24.297
And you believe what you believe strictly because of biological and chemical determinants.

32:25.238 --> 32:30.344
And therefore, on the basis of that, there's really no reason for you to trust your thinking.

32:30.364 --> 32:31.986
There's no reason for you to reason.

32:32.258 --> 32:33.400
Everything is relative.

32:35.382 --> 32:39.828
The last 30 years, people have been saying, because there is no truth.

32:41.630 --> 32:43.453
We're free, our minds are free to think.

32:44.234 --> 32:49.921
In the old days, we thought that there was a God and there was the Bible, and we thought that there was this and that, so we couldn't be free thinkers.

32:50.782 --> 32:53.065
But now we know everything is relative.

32:53.666 --> 32:55.428
There probably is no God.

32:55.449 --> 32:57.391
There certainly is no Bible in Revelation.

32:57.752 --> 32:59.634
So we're free, but you know what that leads to?

33:00.162 --> 33:09.752
For about 30 or 40 years, people were saying, because all things are relative, therefore, because all morals are relative, therefore we shouldn't impose our values on each other.

33:11.755 --> 33:12.696
But that doesn't make sense.

33:15.238 --> 33:18.622
If all morality is relative, why not impose your values on other people?

33:19.703 --> 33:23.347
That's just your value that says you shouldn't impose your value on other people.

33:23.367 --> 33:26.371
You see, if there is no truth, don't you see that?

33:26.831 --> 33:29.554
There is no basis for freedom of thought at all.

33:30.114 --> 33:31.596
I'll control your thought if I want to.

33:34.419 --> 33:35.480
You see, I'll do whatever I want.

33:36.941 --> 33:42.187
The postmodern deconstructionists say, because all values are socially constructed.

33:42.507 --> 33:43.549
There is no right and wrong.

33:45.751 --> 33:49.695
The purpose of life is not to try to find out what is truth and what is justice and conform to it.

33:49.895 --> 33:50.516
Absolutely not.

33:50.776 --> 33:55.021
You do whatever the heck you want, which means that there is no search for truth.

33:55.502 --> 33:56.603
There's no reason to reason.

33:56.623 --> 33:57.404
There's no reason to think.

33:57.444 --> 33:58.405
It's all power struggle.

33:58.445 --> 33:59.666
Whoever has the power

34:00.034 --> 34:02.717
Whoever comes out on top is the one who rules.

34:02.777 --> 34:03.958
We don't find out what is right.

34:03.978 --> 34:04.839
We don't find out what is wrong.

34:04.859 --> 34:05.800
There is no right and wrong.

34:06.300 --> 34:09.103
Don't you see scientific materialism leads to the death of thinking.

34:09.383 --> 34:10.284
You don't need to think.

34:10.304 --> 34:11.926
You can't trust your thinking.

34:13.127 --> 34:14.828
That's the first basic philosophy you've got.

34:14.848 --> 34:19.413
The second basic philosophy is Eastern monism, Eastern pantheism, Eastern religions.

34:20.134 --> 34:22.436
You know what they believe about rationality, they believe.

34:23.217 --> 34:28.882
And anyone will tell you this who understands the New Age and understands the Eastern religion.

34:29.058 --> 34:35.587
is that they believe that what's wrong with us is that we think, that we're rational, that we reason.

34:37.390 --> 34:44.599
Eastern meditation is after what they call, quote, pure awareness without thought, unquote.

34:44.619 --> 34:45.961
Pure awareness without thought.

34:46.502 --> 34:52.190
Eastern meditation says what you need to see is that it's all one, you're one with a tree, you're one with nature.

34:53.672 --> 34:55.154
There is no individuality.

34:55.458 --> 35:08.132
And Eastern thought tries to frustrate the reason, tries to frustrate your analysis, says that eventually we're all gonna go back into the all soul and there won't be individualism and there won't be individuals, there won't be personality, there won't be rationality, there won't be rationality, we'll all be one.

35:08.152 --> 35:24.530
Eastern religion gives you no basis for rationality, but Christianity, or I should say the religion of the Bible, Judaism and Christianity and even Islam, which is based very much on the Bible, they believe, the religion of the Bible teaches that there was a God who created the world who was rational

35:26.050 --> 35:31.115
And if there is a God who is rational, my reason is not an accident of molecules.

35:31.676 --> 35:33.197
And my reason is not an illusion.

35:33.638 --> 35:36.321
My reason is a reflection of his person.

35:37.322 --> 35:45.730
And it means that if a rational and orderly God created the world, then when I use my reason, I'm going to find out what's really out there.

35:45.750 --> 35:53.458
I can't go into this any further, but I want you to know that philosophically, at the end of the 20th century,

35:54.178 --> 36:00.904
Christianity is the only thing in the world, the only thing in the world tonight that really encourages you to use your mind.

36:02.646 --> 36:05.409
It's the only thing in the world tonight that gives you a basis for doing it.

36:07.150 --> 36:09.813
And it's the only thing in the world that really liberates the thinking.

36:10.033 --> 36:11.915
Ah, somebody says, what are you talking about?

36:12.155 --> 36:14.598
I got out of Christianity because I thought I couldn't be liberated.

36:14.878 --> 36:16.579
Now I can think of whatever I want to think about.

36:17.200 --> 36:17.961
Let me tell you something.

36:18.001 --> 36:21.244
The Bible says that you're not free unless you know the truth.

36:21.324 --> 36:22.505
The truth will set you free.

36:22.525 --> 36:23.506
And you know why?

36:24.642 --> 36:28.328
Look at all the people who really understood the truth and said, the Bible is the truth.

36:28.749 --> 36:29.370
That's freedom.

36:29.390 --> 36:29.811
You know why?

36:30.272 --> 36:40.670
No matter what your friends tell you, no matter what your political party tells you, no matter what the ideology tells you, no matter what the dictator or the king who's ready to cut your head off tells you, you know what's the truth.

36:42.493 --> 36:47.862
Because you see, if you have the Bible, if you know there is an absolute truth, you could be the only person in the whole world.

36:47.882 --> 36:50.226
It could be you against the entire world and you can know you're right.

36:52.802 --> 36:55.765
Go look at Elijah standing before Ahab.

36:56.446 --> 36:58.568
Look at Moses standing before Pharaoh.

36:58.788 --> 37:01.791
Look at Paul standing before Herod Agrippa.

37:02.892 --> 37:13.122
Look at Polycarp, you know, in ADAD, the old man standing in the Colosseum and they were about to throw him to the lions and he says away with you all and he dies.

37:13.583 --> 37:16.466
Look at Latimer and Ridley being burned at the stake.

37:16.906 --> 37:18.788
Look at Martin Luther standing before the whole world.

37:19.349 --> 37:20.850
These were free thinkers.

37:21.698 --> 37:27.884
because they knew, because they had submitted the truth, and now they had a standard by which they could judge any ideology.

37:28.304 --> 37:30.607
They had a standard by which they could judge any philosophy.

37:31.528 --> 37:33.249
They weren't the victims of their culture anymore.

37:33.590 --> 37:34.791
They weren't the victims of their party.

37:35.011 --> 37:40.717
They were always able to judge their own culture and their own party and their own philosophy and their own school.

37:43.880 --> 37:48.925
I tell you, Christianity tonight is the only basis for being a free thinker.

37:49.045 --> 37:50.226
It's the only basis.

37:50.754 --> 37:53.298
and encouragement for actually using your mind.

37:54.540 --> 37:57.445
And to conclude, if you don't believe it, let me tell you why.

37:57.465 --> 38:00.771
If you let me tell you why Christianity stimulates the use of the mind.

38:01.111 --> 38:02.414
I can private to you historically.

38:03.175 --> 38:12.390
Wherever there's been revivals, great awakenings in the history of the world, you will see that the common people always receive the gospel.

38:12.450 --> 38:16.978
You go back to the New Testament and it says the common people heard Jesus gladly.

38:17.794 --> 38:21.420
Well, all the religious leaders thought that that proves that he couldn't be a great teacher.

38:21.661 --> 38:23.183
Look at the common people like you.

38:23.484 --> 38:24.786
The common people are following you.

38:25.367 --> 38:28.452
And of course, all through the early church, they were all the common people.

38:28.492 --> 38:29.194
They were the slaves.

38:29.214 --> 38:29.915
They were the illiterates.

38:29.935 --> 38:30.656
And what happened?

38:30.676 --> 38:31.718
Their minds woke up.

38:32.399 --> 38:35.284
The gospel always arouses the thinking.

38:36.065 --> 38:43.378
And throughout the history of the church, throughout the history of the world, whatever the gospel has spread amongst people, their minds wake up and they want schools.

38:44.578 --> 38:47.461
Look at Dartmouth, look at Princeton, you know where they came from?

38:47.621 --> 38:54.469
There was a great awakening in this country, the 1730s, 40s and 50s, and the people who never cared about reading and writing.

38:54.810 --> 39:00.256
When they became Christians, they said, I want to think, I'm a human being now, I'm not an animal anymore, I thought I was.

39:00.957 --> 39:05.121
I want to think, I want to read, I want to write, and those were schools, started out of the revival.

39:07.484 --> 39:10.207
The gospel always makes you gird up your mind, and you know why?

39:11.048 --> 39:12.690
Because the gospel's not a teaching.

39:14.562 --> 39:16.786
The gospel's not a philosophy that says, here, live in this way.

39:17.026 --> 39:17.987
Just live in this way.

39:18.849 --> 39:19.630
That doesn't make you think.

39:19.991 --> 39:25.660
The gospel says, God has broken into the world in the form of Jesus Christ.

39:26.120 --> 39:29.746
And Jesus Christ is the Son of God, and He died for us, and He was raised from the dead.

39:30.047 --> 39:30.527
Don't you see?

39:30.888 --> 39:34.634
You can't even listen to that teaching without it electrifying the mind.

39:34.714 --> 39:35.736
It challenges the mind.

39:35.756 --> 39:36.557
It shocks the mind.

39:36.877 --> 39:39.762
It's not at all like a philosophy.

39:40.002 --> 39:40.743
of how to live.

39:40.783 --> 39:42.446
That doesn't stir up the mind.

39:42.486 --> 39:43.567
The gospel stirs up the mind.

39:43.587 --> 39:48.354
You can't even reject the gospel without using your mind because the claims are so incredible.

39:49.175 --> 39:50.417
God has broken into history.

39:51.298 --> 40:02.354
When the time had fully come, God sent His Son, born under the law, to redeem those under the law, that we might receive the full rights as sons of God.

40:02.690 --> 40:08.736
That claim is so incredible that you can't even reject the gospel without thinking, because you've got to say, well, what's the evidence for the resurrection?

40:08.756 --> 40:10.617
And how do I know these things?

40:10.698 --> 40:12.059
And it's so stunning.

40:12.079 --> 40:14.281
It's so challenging, because the gospel makes you think.

40:14.361 --> 40:15.222
It wakes you up.

40:15.642 --> 40:19.426
The gospel always makes you gird up the loins of your mind.

40:19.466 --> 40:20.106
Have you done that?

40:20.166 --> 40:21.668
Have you submitted your mind to him?

40:22.969 --> 40:32.498
There's only two kinds of people here tonight, the one kind are the people who think that Christianity is something maybe that might help them privately, spiritually,

40:32.642 --> 40:37.458
But they really are afraid to actually let it challenge their mind.

40:38.121 --> 40:44.402
If Jesus is who He said He is, you must belong to Him wholly, intellectually, emotionally, and volitionally.

40:45.634 --> 40:50.341
If he's the son of God, as he said, if he rose from the dead, as it was claimed, you have to look at that evidence.

40:50.361 --> 40:53.365
You can't just say, well, I don't know what I think about all I think.

40:53.385 --> 40:56.210
I just want to have a kind of personal mystical experience.

40:56.250 --> 40:57.111
I just want to have peace.

40:57.131 --> 40:57.872
You can't do it.

40:58.152 --> 40:59.795
The Bible says, I will not.

41:00.155 --> 41:02.839
God says, I will not come into your life unless I come in through your mind.

41:02.879 --> 41:05.643
You have to receive the form of teaching.

41:06.004 --> 41:07.486
You have to look at the evidence.

41:07.506 --> 41:08.407
You have to believe it.

41:08.988 --> 41:09.990
You have to check it out.

41:11.071 --> 41:12.914
Don't you dare try to do it and run around the mind.

41:13.506 --> 41:15.549
Listen to the gospel, let it argue with you.

41:15.929 --> 41:33.693
And lastly, friends, some of your Christians, but you're not very consistent Christians because really you're, so many people come out of fundamentalist or come out of liberal or come out, all these different churches I told you and they all really do a bypass the mind.

41:33.753 --> 41:35.416
Don't you dare, you need to study the word of God.

41:35.456 --> 41:37.238
You have to let the word of God sink in.

41:37.959 --> 41:43.186
You've got to let your mind be completely bathed in the authority of God.

41:44.002 --> 41:45.444
Gird up the loins of your mind.

41:46.605 --> 41:47.106
Let's pray.

41:47.126 --> 41:59.803
Father, we ask that You would just enable us to do the very thing we've been looking at, to submit to You intellectually, to submit to You rationally, to submit every area of our lives to You that we might be holy Yours.

42:01.005 --> 42:02.246
Enable us to do that now.

42:02.727 --> 42:03.969
We ask it in Jesus' name.

42:04.630 --> 42:05.010
Amen.

42:10.658 --> 42:14.585
Thanks for listening to today's teaching from Tim Keller here at Gospel and Life.

42:15.187 --> 42:21.198
For the 40 days from Ash Wednesday through Good Friday, Gospel and Life would like to email you a daily lint devotional.

42:21.639 --> 42:25.406
You can sign up to receive these daily emails at gospelandlife.com.

42:26.007 --> 42:27.830
That's gospelandlife.com.

42:29.253 --> 42:31.858
Today's sermon was recorded in 1993.

42:32.034 --> 42:41.522
The sermons and talks you hear on the Gospel and Life podcast were recorded between 1989 and 2017, while Dr. Keller was senior pastor at Redeemer Presbyterian Church.

